reviewText: Pretty Jude lives with her hypochondriacal mom, fussy-but-funny grandma and kindly invalid grandpa. As a new high school graduate, her small-town life is in a rut, but it's a familiar rut so she continues. Then her grandpa dies, her grandma gets lung cancer, her friend Riley asks her to go on a road trip to Hollywood, and her boyfriend Dean asks her to marry him. When her Aunt and Uncle start a big argument to sell grandma's house, Jude doesn't know which way to turn. She breaks up with Dean and tells Riley she's ready to leave town right then, but Riley chickens out. Jude's mom and healed-up grandma encourage her to explore and have new adventures. The movie ends with Jude driving solo down the road to parts unexplored. Everyone will recognize something of themselves in this interesting, original film. *****
Title: Searching for Wooden Watermelons

reviewText: Excellent independent film with a great message, no sex scenes or violence. The cinematography in this film is superb, and all the acting is superb. It's a sweet film that will surely open up your eyes, and make you realize that you have to take risks in life. Definitely a well directed movie, that everyone should see!Jude Farnie is twenty-five years old, and life in the isolated community of Beaumont, Texas is all she's ever known.Content to care for her mother Grace and her elderly grandmother Nofia, Jude's inexplicable stagnation betrays her deep-rooted desire to strike out on her own life-adventure.Upon graduating from college for the third time, however, Joy quickly discovers that the only thing she fears more than change is things staying just the way they currently are, and always have been.
Title: Searching for Wooden Watermelons

reviewText: This film is about a young woman with analysis paralysis who finally takes a leap of faith to follow her own dreams.  I had never heard of any of the actors before and really enjoyed them.  Every time the grandmother spoke she reminded me of Dolly Parton.
